complete_model_interaction.output:
Step-by-step reasoning:
1. In the Fehr-Schmidt model, players experience disutility from inequitable outcomes. When a responder receives more than the opponent, they may still reject the offer because the advantageous inequality (getting more than the opponent) causes them guilt.
2. Because the data always has split_self > split_opp for responders, we only need to model the aversion to advantageous inequality.
3. The mathematical form for the utility of accepting an offer is therefore:
  U_accept = split_self – β · (split_self – split_opp)
4. Here, split_self and split_opp are observed monetary values. The parameter beta (β) is a learnable parameter capturing the weight participants place on the inequity (guilt) they experience when getting more than their opponent.
5. The model predicts the responder’s utility for accepting the offer (the utility of rejection is 0 and is not modeled). Lower (i.e., negative) utility indicates unlikelihood of acceptance.
6. This model uses one learnable parameter (β). Its numerical bounds are set generously, for example between 0 and 10.

Below is the formal specification:

<MODEL>
U = split_self - beta*(split_self - split_opp)
</MODEL>

<VARIABLES>
{
  "variables": {
    "U": {
      "description": "Utility of accepting the offer",
      "range": {
        "min": "-inf",
        "max": "inf",
        "inclusive_min": true,
        "inclusive_max": true
      },
      "learnable": false,
      "source": "calculated"
    },
    "split_self": {
      "description": "Monetary share for the participant (in £)",
      "range": {
        "min": 0,
        "max": "inf",
        "inclusive_min": true,
        "inclusive_max": false
      },
      "learnable": false,
      "source": "data"
    },
    "split_opp": {
      "description": "Monetary share for the opponent (in £)",
      "range": {
        "min": 0,
        "max": "inf",
        "inclusive_min": true,
        "inclusive_max": false
      },
      "learnable": false,
      "source": "data"
    },
    "beta": {
      "description": "Advantageous inequality aversion (guilt) parameter capturing the disutility of receiving more than the opponent",
      "range": {
        "min": 0,
        "max": 10,
        "inclusive_min": true,
        "inclusive_max": true
      },
      "learnable": true,
      "source": "learnable"
    }
  }
}
</VARIABLES>

<SUMMARY>
A Fehr-Schmidt model for the responder in which the utility of accepting an offer is computed as the participant’s monetary share reduced by a penalty proportional to the advantageous inequality relative to the opponent, with a single learnable parameter beta governing sensitivity to this inequity.
</SUMMARY>

